T1  - ON THE LIVING ARRANGEMENTS OF ELDERLY WIDOWS*
AU  - Bethencourt, Carlos
AU  - Ríos-Rull, José-Víctor
Y1  - 2009/08/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00548.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 773
EP  - 801
VL  - 50
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00548.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Between 1970 and 1990, the share of elderly widows living alone grew by 23.2% in the United States, whereas those living with their children decreased by a similar amount. We pose a variety of models for determining the living arrangements in which living together increases consumption because of economies of scale and may also provide utility directly. We estimate these models using the 1970 data and obtain an excellent fit. The estimated models predict that changes in the incomes of both the widow and her offspring generate three-quarters of the increase in the number of widows living alone.
ER  - 

